the choir. The - the - the clergyman, Mr Cunningham - he was a - a sporty individual, he - he - he'd been a - he'd been in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - blue, a - a - a rowing - a rowing one you see. Well in his house in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Roseberry Crescent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he had a - one of these - h
is - one of his oars up on the - on the wall. And - some of his pals in the - in the congregation was one - one called - Tompson. He was chief clerk - to the Secretary of Scotland. Of course - and - and - it's different now of course. He was the Secretary
 for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - with the post office you see, and his room was up the stair, and Thompson was his chief clerk and he was a member of the congregation, and he - he took boys from - there was several of us went to - to - the post office through this chap Thom
pson. There was a chap Little, and he was in the choir, and his brother - last time I heard of him he was headmaster at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Southbridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school That's a - a while ago, but - oh - his brother was in the post office. In fact there was two brothers in the post office, and - Lane the fish merchant and - Castle - used to be {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Castle Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - away now long ago - his son was in the choir. And he went to the post office.
